    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, but if it's ambiguous, how do we actually map that out in a tree? If I'm drawing it, am I supposed to show both possibilities? Also, you mentioned \"branches\"—does the structural hierarchy technically change how we classify the attachment? I'm a bit lost on the formal way to explain the difference between VP-attachment and NP-attachment.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the world of syntax trees, ambiguity is a real thing, and if you don't want to show both possibilities, you're usually going to have to make a choice based on what sounds most \"right\" or what the grammar rules you're studying prioritize. Sometimes, it's just a matter of convention, like deciding which path is the main path for the main action.\n\nThe structural hierarchy absolutely changes how you classify the attachment. When you attach a phrase to the Verb Phrase (VP), you're saying the prepositional phrase is describing *how* the action was done. If you attach it to the Noun Phrase (NP), you're saying it's describing *which* man or *which* telescope. It's all about the head of the phrase you are trying to modify.",
      "source": "target",
