    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense for the difference in meaning. Can you give me a more technical breakdown of the constituent structure for both? Like, if I'm using X-bar theory to map it out, how does the specifier or the complement change when the PP is part of the NP vs. being an adjunct to the VP?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "X-bar theory is a good framework for this, but it can get really dense, especially when you're dealing with these tricky attachments. If you're mapping it out, you're essentially looking at how the phrase structure rules stack up.\n\nWhen the prepositional phrase (\"with the telescope\") attaches to the **Noun Phrase (NP)**, it usually gets slotted in as an adjunct modifying the Noun itself, often appearing in a specifier position or as a modifier within the NP structure. For example, the NP structure might look something like: $\\text{NP} \\rightarrow \\text{N} \\ \\text{PP}$. In this case, the telescope is part of the *thing* being discussed.\n\nIf it attaches to the **Verb Phrase (VP)**, it functions as an adjunct modifying the VP, often sitting in a position that modifies the verb or the entire action complex. The VP structure would incorporate this PP as an adjunct to the VP, perhaps looking like: $\\text{VP} \\rightarrow \\text{V} \\ \\text{NP} \\ \\text{PP}$. This means the telescope is describing *how* the seeing happened.",
      "source": "target",
